x4codes.hlp: California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA, United States of America

x4freetext: The ONR-CIT tandem accelerator.
A 10.2*10.2 cm NaI(Tl) crystal which was
adjustable in radius and angle (in one plane) about the
target. Most of the data were taken with a 30.5 cm
diameter cylindrical lead shield around the crystal;
however, where angles greater than 90 degr. were
involved this lead shield was removed and the bare
crystal used. Removing the cylindrical shield resulted
in a 55% increase in room background in the energy
region of interest to his experiment. Beam deposition
of natural carbon on the targets was minimized by the
use of an in-line liquid nitrogen cold trap and ion
pumping at the target chamber.
Energy error
REACTION records and data tables in Subents
008, 009 were changed.

x4headers.headerHelp: Uncertainty in incident projectile energy

x4freetext: Data represent the number of pulses per microcoulomb
of He+ ions observed within a window corresponding to
gamma ray energies from 0.8 Ex to 1.1 Ex, where Ex is
the appropriate excitation energy in 16O determined
from the bombarding energy Ea by using the relation
The NaI(Tl) crystal was set at 45 degr. to the beam
axis with its face approximately 2 cm from the target
spot.
Targets were prepared by cracking 12C enriched
acetylene onto a backing of 0.025 cm tantalum. The
target surface was at 45 degr. to the beam axis and
parallel to the face of the crystal.
The data have been corrected for dead time losses
(always under 7%) and time dependent room background.

x4freetext: Data represent the number of counts per 450 mu-C of
He++ ions in the 0.8 Ex to 1.1 Ex interval.
The NaI(Tl) crystal was set at 7.6 cm from the target
spot.
Enriched 12C target was used. The target was
perpendicular to the beam.
Corrections have been made for room background and dead
time.

x4freetext: Data represent the number of pulses observed
within a window corresponding to gamma ray energies
from 2.91 to 5.20 MeV for a bombardment of 3 mu-C of
He++.
The NaI(Tl) crystal was set at 45 degr. to the beam
axis with its face 14.3 cm from the target spot.
Carbon target depleted by a factor of approximately 10
in 13C content from that of natural carbon have been
used. The target was prepared by cracking methane onto
a 0.025 cm tantalum backing.
